  "prompt": "Does a voltmeter show RMS voltage?",
  "response": "A typical voltmeter, especially those commonly used in household and general applications, shows the RMS (Root Mean Square) voltage when measuring AC (alternating current). RMS voltage is a representation of the effective or \u201cwork-equivalent\u201d voltage value. For sinusoidal waveforms, the RMS voltage is approximately 0.707 times the peak voltage. \n\nHowever, not all voltmeters measure RMS voltage accurately for waveforms other than pure sine waves. Basic digital multimeters may assume a sine wave shape and apply a simple multiplication factor to approximate RMS voltage. True RMS voltmeters and multimeters are designed to accurately measure the RMS value regardless of waveform shape, including complex waveforms such as those with harmonics or nonsinusoidal patterns.\n\nSo, if you're using a true RMS voltmeter or multimeter, it will show the correct RMS voltage for any waveform. If you're using a simpler meter that assumes a sine wave, it will be accurate for traditional sinusoidal AC but may be inaccurate for other waveform shapes.",
